          <td bgcolor="" valign="top" width="1"><img src="/magination/gfx/trans_header1.gif" width="22" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
  <tr>
    <td>
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
        <tr>
          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chpurple"><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Cald Direct Damage = Fun?<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.17)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=8891'>Simon "dReshHyren" Pang</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=8891&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 24, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> The Cald, the land of fire and flame, has several different types of decks.  My personal favorite is Direct Damage.  This is because I don’t have to rely on attacking, so playing Creatures after the Attack Phase doesn’t bother me at all.  This type of deck is focused on using Spells and Creature Powers to overwhelm the opponent, thus, eliminating the absolute need for attacking.  This type of deck is normally very powerful against Swarm type decks, but can have trouble with Arderial/Orothe control and some variant on a Dark Twins deck (but who doesn’t?).<br>
<br>
The Creatures<br>
The heart of every Direct Damage deck would have to be the Ergar.  This amazing Creature gives all of your Cald Creatures the Power, Spark, which allows them to pay one energy to remove one energy from any other Creature or Magi.  While this one for one trade may not seem like the greatest thing in the world, it gets very annoying when put together with the Scroll of Fire, which then allows you to remove two energy for one.  Another Creature that aids this is the Ithapher, which allows you to remove yet another energy every time you Spark, giving you an amazing three for one trade.  Also going along with Ergars are the Giant Arbolls.  While they don’t offer up any sort of direct damage at first, they go extremely well with Ergars because they get to Spark for free.  They also gain from other Creatures using Spark as well.  Having multiple Ergars out can be a real pain for your opponent because it will allow your Creatures to Spark multiple times.  Yes, I’ve been questioned on this many times.  If you don’t believe me, check out http://www.magiduel.com/rc_creatures.html#ergar and find out there.<br>
Other prominent Creatures that aid this direct damage theme are the Diomant and Magma Hyren.  With the Diomant, you can remove four energy from any one Magi for only one energy (per Energy Transfer and Flame Hunt), and Magma Hyren has it’s own built in Fireball for Magi.  Both of these can become extremely powerful when an Abraxin’s Crown is out.  Out-of-region, there’s the Core Grag, which although it is Core, is very powerful, especially versus swarm decks.  These six Creatures are the core (no pun intended) of Direct Damage, although the Ithapher may be omitted to make the deck more concise.<br>
Although I don’t use many other direct damage Creatures, there are many out there, some of the more powerful being: Fire Chogo and Greater Vaal.  Fire Chogo is like a compact Wildfire, and Greater Vaal is wonderful for taking out Magi.  The reason I don’t use either is because they take up space (which could be used for more valuable cards) and because I have very bad luck with rolling dice.<br>
Cald also has a wide assortment of Creatures that don’t necessarily go with the Direct Damage theme that I use in my deck.  Braggles, most noted, are a great annoyance to any type of deck.  Magma Hyrens can give them energy, then you can transform them into any region you want.  Another one of my personal favorites would be the Raxis.  This baby can eliminate all those pesky Relics (**cough**Rayje’s Belt**cough**) or force an opposing Magi to spend four energy if he/she really wants to keep the Relic in play.  I prefer Raxis over Relic Stalker because they can Spark Creatures/Magi.  Relic Stalkers… can’t.<br>
<br>
The Magi<br>
There’s not really much to say about Magi.  I start out with Barak because he has a strong starting energy and an anti-Corrupt (more or less), Arbolit.  I can also use Barak to get the Creatures I need.  I tend to use Magi that have standard energizes, due to the fact that I need to play Creatures to Spark with.  I don’t want this to sound like my deck strategy, so I’ll just go over some of the other Magi that could possibly be useful in a Direct Damage deck.<br>
Gar is a helpful last Magi.  Starting with 19 (after energize), he can play a variety of Creatures, and keep them alive by Strengthening them.  I tend to save an Ergar or two for him, if I know that I can’t beat the opponent with my current Magi (which very rarely happens).<br>
For those of you who enjoy chance, Grega may be a great choice.  She’s won me a game before, but just barely.  Starting with 15 (after energize), she doesn’t really make that impressive of a Magi, but if you have good luck with dice (which I wish I had), her Thermal Blast can be extremely helpful.<br>
Valkan isn’t that great of a Magi in a Direct Damage deck, unless you’re going for Spell Burn theme.  If you go for a creatureless or less-creature deck, reliant on Spells, he’s the way to go.  Nara can be helpful in protecting your Ergars, but other than that, she doesn’t have much of a use.<br>
Raega is amazing.  She essentially attacks a Creature by herself.  This in a way can be helpful, but also hindering.  Because she has to remove energy from herself, it becomes pretty hard to keep her in play for a long time.<br>
Vorga’s an amazing Magi (second in my deck).  She can control the board very well, and due to her amazing starting hand, she is a great choice for any deck.  Amanax may, however, not be such a great choice.  He seemed pretty good to me at first, and he worked very well in theory, but when put to the test, he burned out too quickly.<br>
<br>
The Relics<br>
The most obvious Relic you’re going to want to use is the Scroll of Fire.  With Ergars (as explained before), all of your Cald Creatures can pay one to deal two damage.  This can also compliment Core Grag, Spells, etc.  The Heat Lens is also very helpful, forcing your opponent to discard a card from their hand, eliminating huge threats.  However, it becomes very costly, so using it will hinder the speed of the deck.<br>
Cald has a problem with drawing cards, so Gorgle’s Glasses may be a good choice for you, especially if you’re discarding lots of Creatures with Powers.  Abraxin’s Crown is amazing!  This has helped me pull off wins the turn before the opponent would have defeated me.  Great with Diomants, Spells, etc.  Again, if you like rolling dice, Grega’s Ring will be a choice Relic for you, but my paranoia prevents me from using it.<br>
I also like to use Rayje’s Sword to counter Burrow decks, Zannah and KT (as well as other things).  You may have to be careful using this, however, because it can hurt Braggle as well.<br>
<br>
The Spells<br>
For a Cald Direct Damage deck, you’re probably not going to want to use too many Spells, so that you can maximize the amount of Creatures you fit in the deck.  I prefer Storm Cloud over Shockwave because it works with Scroll of Fire, and isn’t Entombed as often.  I use Syphon Vortex as a way of keeping those huge Creatures in check.  A lot of the Fireball variants are also good, and with Abraxin’s Crown, they can be used on Magi as well.<br>
<br>
For an example of a Cald Direct Damage deck, check out Pyromania v1.5 (or whatever my current version is).<br>
